[m
[1mNAME[0m[m
       journalctl - Query the systemd journal[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       [1mjournalctl[0m [OPTIONS...] [MATCHES...][m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       [1mjournalctl[0m may be used to query the contents of the [1msystemd[0m(1) journal as written by [1msystemd-journald.service[0m(8).[m
[m
       If called without parameters, it will show the full contents of the journal, starting with the oldest entry collected.[m
[m
       If one or more match arguments are passed, the output is filtered accordingly. A match is in the format "FIELD=VALUE", e.g.[m
       "_SYSTEMD_UNIT=httpd.service", referring to the components of a structured journal entry. See [1msystemd.journal-fields[0m(7) for a list[m
       of well-known fields. If multiple matches are specified matching different fields, the log entries are filtered by both, i.e. the[m
       resulting output will show only entries matching all the specified matches of this kind. If two matches apply to the same field,[m
       then they are automatically matched as alternatives, i.e. the resulting output will show entries matching any of the specified[m
       matches for the same field. Finally, the character "+" may appear as a separate word between other terms on the command line. This[m
       causes all matches before and after to be combined in a disjunction (i.e. logical OR).[m
[m
       It is also possible to filter the entries by specifying an absolute file path as an argument. The file path may be a file or a[m
       symbolic link and the file must exist at the time of the query. If a file path refers to an executable binary, an "_EXE=" match[m
       for the canonicalized binary path is added to the query. If a file path refers to an executable script, a "_COMM=" match for the[m
       script name is added to the query. If a file path refers to a device node, "_KERNEL_DEVICE=" matches for the kernel name of the[m
       device and for each of its ancestor devices is added to the query. Symbolic links are dereferenced, kernel names are synthesized,[m
       and parent devices are identified from the environment at the time of the query. In general, a device node is the best proxy for[m
       an actual device, as log entries do not usually contain fields that identify an actual device. For the resulting log entries to be[m
       correct for the actual device, the relevant parts of the environment at the time the entry was logged, in particular the actual[m
       device corresponding to the device node, must have been the same as those at the time of the query. Because device nodes generally[m
       change their corresponding devices across reboots, specifying a device node path causes the resulting entries to be restricted to[m
       those from the current boot.[m
[m
       Additional constraints may be added using options [1m--boot[0m, [1m--unit=[0m, etc., to further limit what entries will be shown (logical[m
       AND).[m
[m
       Output is interleaved from all accessible journal files, whether they are rotated or currently being written, and regardless of[m
       whether they belong to the system itself or are accessible user journals. The [1m--header[0m option can be used to identify which files[m
       [4mare[24m being shown.[m
[m
       The set of journal files which will be used can be modified using the [1m--user[0m, [1m--system[0m, [1m--directory[0m, and [1m--file[0m options, see[m
       below.[m
[m
       All users are granted access to their private per-user journals. However, by default, only root and users who are members of a few[m
       special groups are granted access to the system journal and the journals of other users. Members of the groups "systemd-journal",[m
       "adm", and "wheel" can read all journal files. Note that the two latter groups traditionally have additional privileges specified[m
       by the distribution. Members of the "wheel" group can often perform administrative tasks.[m
[m
       The output is paged through [1mless[0m by default, and long lines are "truncated" to screen width. The hidden part can be viewed by[m
       using the left-arrow and right-arrow keys. Paging can be disabled; see the [1m--no-pager[0m option and the "Environment" section below.[m
[m
       When outputting to a tty, lines are colored according to priority: lines of level ERROR and higher are colored red; lines of level[m
       NOTICE and higher are highlighted; lines of level DEBUG are colored lighter grey; other lines are displayed normally.[m
